    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-12-16T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-12-16T15:00:00-05:00" n="136"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d136">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A3/1854: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-12-16T20:00:00+00:00"
                            >December 16, 1936—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received December 16—4:17 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>618. My 617, December 16, 6 p.m.<note n="40" xml:id="d136fn40">Not
                        printed.</note> Foreign Office states this afternoon Japanese Ambassador
                    orally informed them that Japanese Government is giving favorable consideration
                    to the two proposals in question; (1), as regards “C” class cruisers, (2),
                    Japanese Government to escalate to retain submarines.</p>
                <pb facs="0234" n="154" xml:id="pg_154"/>
                <p>Yoshida explained this really meant complete acceptance but before formal
                    Japanese reply can be made it must be passed by Cabinet.</p>
                <p>Craigie says First Lord<note n="41" xml:id="d136fn41">Sir Samuel Hoare, First
                        Lord of the British Admiralty.</note> will make statement in Parliament
                    tomorrow in this connection stating in substance that exchange of views has
                    taken place with United States and Japan. United States has replied if Britain
                    has recourse to escalator clause they have no objection and British Government
                    has reason to believe Japanese Government’s reply will be favorable.</p>
                <p>Yoshida has agreed to above.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bingham</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
